SIMPLE: ripen
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ripen
<hw>Rip"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Ripened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ripening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To grow ripe; to
become mature, as grain, fruit, flowers, and the like; <as>as, grapes
<ex>ripen</ex> in the sun</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To approach or come to perfection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ripen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ripen
<hw>Rip"en</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to mature;
to make ripe; <as>as, the warm days <ex>ripened</ex> the
corn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mature; to fit or prepare; to bring to
perfection; <as>as, to <ex>ripen</ex> the judgment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When faith and love, which parted from thee never,⟦br⟧
Had <qex>ripined</qex> thy iust soul to dwell with God.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ripeness</ent>⟦br⟧
